  <div class="flex items-cejnter gap-4 mb-6">
    <p class="text-justify leading-tight text-sm">
      In collaboration with the Clinical Tumor Analysis Consortyium (CPTAC) 
      and the International Cancer Proteogenome Consortium (ICPC), we apply 
      multiomics integration methods to define the proteomic landscape with the goal o better understanding the tumor biology across tumor types: 
<b>Breast Cancer</b> (<i><u><a href="https://doi.org/10.1038/nature18003" target="_blank">Mertins et al., Nature 2016</a></u></i>, <i><u><a href="https://linkinghub.elsevier.com/retrieve/pii/S0092-8674(20)31400-8" target="_blank">Krug et al., Cell 2020</a></u></i>),
<b>Melanoma</b> (<i><u><a href="https://doi.org/10.1101/2023.09.29.559755" target="_blank">Kuras et al., bioRxixv2023</a></u></i>).
We are also exploring the similarities between cancer types through
<b>pan-camcer analysis:</b> integration of proteome comics with histology using deep learning (<i><u><a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.xcrm.2023.101173" target="_blank">Wang et al., Cell Reports Medicine 2023</a></u></i>) and exploration of the immune landscape (<i><u><a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.cell.2024.01.027" target="_blank">Petralia et al., Cell 2024</a></u></i>)

    </p>
